title: For Sale:  INTERDYNAMIC KG-99 MINI 9mm with Threaded Barrel
postcontent: I have a rare and in a very good condition Pre-ban Interdynamic KG-99 mini with threaded barrel (suppressor ready).It comes with with two 32 round magazine and a 100 rounds of Federal 9mm ammo. This is a Swedish company Interdynamic AB of Stockholm, creator of famous MP-9 submachine gun based on the Carl Gustav M45.  Designed for military applications but Interdynamic AB did not find a government contract, so it was brought to US market as an open-bolt semi-automatic KG-9 pistol. KG-9 open bolt design makes it easy to anyone to convert to full auto and because of this, ATF forced Interdynamic to redesign it into a closed-bolt system, to make it harder to anyone to convert to full-auto and this variant was called KG-99. Conversion manual to full auto is still widely available but you have to have a class 3 license legally own a fully automatic weapon. May consider to trade with .223/5.56 ammo in equal value or a 5.7x28mm ammo also in equal value.

Burris 3-9x40mm Fullfield II Rifle Scope w/ Burris 10x32mm Landmark Binoculars gives you a full spot-and-shoot package! This value package from Burris includes the Burris 3x-9x 40mm Fullfield-II Riflescope and the Burris Landmark 10x32mm Binoculars.

The Burris Fullfield II Rifle Scope has a one-piece main tube and eyepiece, Burris envied steel-on-steel adjustment system, and HiLume multi-coatings on every single air to glass lens surface. The Burris FullField-II Scope is even more forgiving for eye position, is a little shorter, and a good bit lighter. The magnification ring and eyepiece have been made into one solid unit requiring only two seals rather than three. To change magnification, simply turn the entire eyepiece. Burris Fullfield 2 Scope eliminated most of the potential leak paths in the eyepiece/power ring area and sealed the remainder with special quad seals instead of O-rings. The adjustment system has been moved to improve mounting options and the European-style adjustable eyepiece requires no locking mechanism. Each scope is filled and purged at least 24 times with high quality, laboratory grade dry nitrogen. Each nitrogen cycle absorbs airborne and residual surface moisture that is evacuated from the scope. Burris uses specially made quad seals to provide double insurance against leakage.

title: Want To Buy:  FEG SMC 918
location: Anywehre in MI, Northern Lower Peninsula, Michigan
postcontent:
The SMC 918 is the smallest of the Makarov caliber pistols exported to the US. I'd really like to find one to add to my Makarov collection before summer hits as it is perfect for CC in the summer.  If anyone knows anything about where to find one, please let me know.

=================

A Polish P64 on top, the FEG SMC 918 on bottom.



 FEG SMC-918

When K.B.I. observed the popularity of the SMC-380 in the U.S., it decided to import the 9mm Makarov version, the SMC-918. The Hungarians had made this model (with slight modifications) since the late 1950s, with importation beginning in late 1994.

The SMC-918 we tested handled well. With its titanium and aluminum frame as well as its clean lines and rounded corners, this pistol carries comfortably in one's pocket and is light and handy. It also boasts good instinctive pointing, with a trigger pull that is noticeably smoother and lighter than that found in the SMC-380s tested. Despite the improved trigger pull, however, the SMC-918 proved slightly less accurate than the SMC-380. Whether this is a quirk of the 9mm Makarov cartridge or an inherent situation is difficult to tell. Regardless, the test pistol had no trouble feeding any ammunition tested, including Hornady's XTP hollowpoint. Recoil with SMC-918 was sharp, similar to firing a small .38-caliber revolver. The shape of its backstrap could be at fault. By rounding off much more than that of the Walther PPK, for instance, the Hungarian designers have created a gun that is smoother in contour but a bit more difficult to fire. Compact guns are, after all, an exercise in compromise.

The SMC-918 offers the 9mm Makarov cartridge in a package that is appreciably smaller and lighter than the Soviet-designed Makarov pistol or its derivatives. The SMC-918 is, in fact, the smallest pistol currently in production for the Makarov round. The price to pay is a gun that is easier to carry and slightly more difficult to shoot. Given its mission of self-defense, though, that's a compromise many buyers will surely find acceptable.
